  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(5) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "And he sought God.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And he continued to seek God",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (the Hebrew is an expression peculiar to the chronicler).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "In the days of Zechariah.—An otherwise unknown prophet.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "In the days of Zechariah.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—An otherwise unknown prophet.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Who had understanding in the visions of God.—Literally, the skilled in seeing God—a surprising epithet, occurring nowhere else. Some Hebrew MSS., and the LXX., Syriac, and Arabic versions, and the Targum, read, “in the fear of God.” This is doubtless correct; and the text should be rendered. “who had understanding (or gave instruction) in the fear of God.” So the famous Rabbis, Rashi and Kimchi, long since suggested. Zechariah was thus the guide and counsellor of king Uzziah, and that not only in religious matters, but in what we should call the political sphere; for in those days the distinction between things sacred and secular, civil and ecclesiastical, between Church and State, religion and common life, was wholly unknown.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Who had understanding in the visions of God.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Literally, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "the skilled in seeing God",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—a surprising epithet, occurring nowhere else. Some Hebrew MSS., and the LXX., Syriac, and Arabic versions, and the Targum, read, “in the fear of God.” This is doubtless correct; and the text should be rendered. “who had understanding (or ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "gave instruction",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ") in the fear of God.” So the famous Rabbis, Rashi and Kimchi, long since suggested. Zechariah was thus the guide and counsellor of king Uzziah, and that not only in religious matters, but in what we should call the political sphere; for in those days the distinction between things sacred and secular, civil and ecclesiastical, between Church and State, religion and common life, was wholly unknown.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And as long as he sought.—Literally, in the days of his seeking.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "And as long as he sought.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Literally, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "in the days of his seeking.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The Lord, God . . .—Such a mode of speech reveals the chronicler’s own hand.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "The Lord, God",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": ". . .",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Such a mode of speech reveals the chronicler’s own hand.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Instead of this verse, 2Kings 15:4 makes the deduction usual in its estimate of the character of a reign: “Only the high places were not taken away; the people still used to sacrifice and burn incense on the high places.”",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Instead of this verse, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Kings 15:4",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " makes the deduction usual in its estimate of the character of a reign: “Only the high places were not taken away; the people still used to sacrifice and burn incense on the high places.”",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The power and prosperity of Uzziah are accounted for by the chronicler on the ground that he sought God during the life of Zechariah; although afterwards he offended by rashly intruding upon the priest’s office, and was punished with leprosy (2Chronicles 26:16-21).",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "The power and prosperity of Uzziah are accounted for by the chronicler on the ground that he sought God during the life of Zechariah; although afterwards he offended by rashly intruding upon the priest’s office, and was punished with leprosy (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Chronicles 26:16-21",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ").",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 26:5",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Chronicles 26:5",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "He sought God in the days of Zechariah ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Who was probably the son of that Zechariah whom his grand-father Joash slew. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Who had understanding in the visions of God — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Either the visions with which he himself was favoured, or the visions of the preceding prophets. He was well skilled in prophecy, and conversed much with the heavenly world; was an intelligent, devout, and good man; and had such influence on Uzziah, that while he lived he ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "sought God, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "sought his favour, direction, and aid; trusted in him, cleaved to him, and persisted in his worship, and in the true religion. Happy are the great men who have such about them, and are willing to be advised by them: but unhappy those who seek God only while they have such with them, and have not a principle in themselves to bear them out to the end.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
